<p><b>Francis C. Speight</b> (May 16, 1816 - March 20, 1877) was an American law enforcement officer and <a href="/wiki/Police_inspector" title="Police inspector" class="mw-redirect">police inspector</a> for the <a href="/wiki/New_York_City_Police_Department" title="New York City Police Department">New York City Police Department</a>. A noted crimefighter, credited for running out the criminal elements from <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a>'s Eighteenth and Nineteenth Wards in the 1850s, he also took part in the <a href="/wiki/New_York_City_Police_Riot" title="New York City Police Riot" class="mw-redirect">Police Riot of 1857</a> and <a href="/wiki/New_York_Draft_Riot" title="New York Draft Riot" class="mw-redirect">New York Draft Riots of 1863</a>. Prior to the outbreak of violence at the <a href="/wiki/Third_Avenue" title="Third Avenue">Third Avenue</a> draft office, Speight was the only officer to maintain control of his station, the <a href="/wiki/Broadway_(Manhattan)" title="Broadway (Manhattan)">Broadway</a> draft office, during the early hours of the riots.<sup id="cite_ref-Asbury_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Asbury-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p></p>
